g.ns0:text: Hierarchical clustering is a powerful method for exploratory data analysis in which data is represented as a tree. Leaves in the tree are individual data points and internal nodes are groupings of data.
In Bayesian hierarchical clustering, we output a probability distribution over possible clusterings.
We propose an interactive Bayesian method for hierarchical clustering, where an algorithm can query a user for feedback to produce better hierarchical clusterings.
Our clustering algorithm produces a candidate tree which is shown to a user. \nThe user can correct an error in the form of a \\emph{triplet}.

In our method, a hierarchical clustering algorithm asks a user for feedback 
on a candidate tree.
The user points out an error in the form of a \emph{triplet}, $(\{a, b\}, c)$, stipulating that
$a$ and $b$ should be in a subtree together without $c$.
It is difficult for a user to find an error in a tree over too many data points.\nWe thus show the user a candidate tree restricted to an $O(1)$\nsubset of the data whereupon they provide a triplet.

Our algorithm then samples candidate trees from a constrained posterior distribution\nusing Metropolis-Hastings. We use the subtree-prune and regraft (SPR) move\nbut limit regraft moves to those that will not violate triplets.

Interactive algorithms all achieve better triplet distance than\ntraditional algorithms at the end of 60000 iterations of Metropolis-Hastings.\nInterleaving random and active querying seems to perform the best.

We are interested in the posterior distribution
of trees given data.
This inference is usually performed 
via approximation algorithms like Metropolis-Hastings.

We accomplish this by first defining a prior distribution over hierarchies, $P(T)$. \nWe then define a likelihood model to conditionally generate a dataset \ngiven a hierarchy sampled from $P(T)$. This generates a dataset $X = \\{x_i\\}_{i = 1}^N$.

We ran our algorithm using the Dirichlet diffusion tree (DDT) prior on several datasets. 
Pictured below are results for the \emph{zoo} dataset.
We measured tree quality via triplet distance, or the fraction of
triplets violated by a tree with respect to ground truth.
We also benchmarked 5 different querying schemes, performing
queries every 100 iterations of the sampler.
